#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:345
msgid ""
"%1 is already available on majority of Linux distributions. It can be "
"installed directly from [Discover](%2), [GNOME Software](%2) or your "
"distribution’s [software store](%2)."
msgstr ""

#. download.source.title
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:348
msgid "Release Sources"
msgstr "リリースソース"

#. download.source.description
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:350
msgid ""
"%1 is released regularly as part of KDE Gear. You can find %1 latest stable "
"release among the [tarballs from the latest KDE Gear release](https://"
"download.kde.org/stable/release-service).\n"
"\n"
"If you want to build %1 from sources, we recommend checking our [Getting "
"Involved](/get-involved) page which contains links to full guide how to "
"compile %1.\n"
msgstr ""

#. download.flatpak.description
#. %1 app name, %2 link, %3 link
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:358
msgid ""
"You can install the latest [%1 flatpak](%2) from Flathub. Experimental "
"flatpaks with nightly builds of %1 can be [installed from the KDE Flatpak "
"repository](%3)."
msgstr ""

#. download.install
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:361
msgid "Installation"
msgstr "インストール"

#. download.install.platform
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:363
msgid ""
"To install %1, follow the instructions of the platform you are using for how "
"to install software. Most platforms have a graphical installer which can be "
"used to install software packages. In many cases it will automatically be "
"opened when clicking the download or install link for your platform. There "
"is a [generic tutorial for installing KDE applications](https://"
"userbase.kde.org/Tutorials/Install_KDE_software) which also can be applied "
"to %1."
msgstr ""

#. download.install.platform.components
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:366
msgid ""
"To install %1 or one of its components as a stand-alone application, follow "
"the instructions of the platform you are using for how to install software. "
"Most platforms have a graphical installer which can be used to install "
"software packages. In many cases it will automatically be opened when "
"clicking the download or install link for your platform. There is a [generic "
"tutorial for installing KDE applications](https://userbase.kde.org/Tutorials/"
"Install_KDE_software) which also can be applied to %1."
msgstr ""

#. download.install.linux
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:369
msgid ""
"If you are using Linux, %1 might already be pre-installed on your system as "
"part of a default selection. If not, you can install it with the package "
"management tool of your Linux distribution. See its documentation for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#. download.install.modular.components
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:372
msgid ""
"In many cases you will have the opportunity to install %1 in a modular way, "
"so you can decide to only install the set of components you actually want to "
"use. Translations of the user interface often also will be available as "
"separate module you can install according to your needs and preferences."
msgstr ""

#. download.uninstall
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:375
msgid "Uninstallation"
msgstr "アンインストール"

#. download.uninstall.instruction
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:377
msgid ""
"To uninstall %1, follow the instructions of the package management tool you "
"have used to install %1. This will remove the %1 application. It will not "
"touch data you have viewed, created, or modified with %1."
msgstr ""

#. download.uninstall.instruction.components
#. %1 app name
#. +> trunk5
#: i18n/en.yaml:380
msgid ""
"To uninstall %1, follow the instructions of the package management tool you "
"have used to install %1 and its components. This will remove the components "
"of your choice. It will not touch data you have viewed, created, or modified "
"with %1."
msgstr ""

